<h2 id="boldend">Boldend</h2>
<p>Boldend, founded in 2017 by Jon Miller and based in San Diego, is a cybersecurity startup. It stays out of the spotlight and calls itself a "SaaS Next-Generation Defense Contractor." The company creates tools for cyber warfare, with an emphasis on automation and advanced intelligence activities. Boldend's tools have reportedly been able to exploit WhatsApp's security to install malicious software on target devices.</p>
<p>Its products include Origen, described as an "all-in-one malware platform" that enables the creation of malware for multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, Mac, and Android. It is designed to hack into devices and extract data. Additionally, Boldend has developed other tools and platforms for surveillance purposes, such as Kevlar (implant analysis), Hedgemaze (traffic obfuscation), and Cricket (Wi-Fi attack hardware). </p>
<p>Boldend has primarily worked with government entities, including various branches of the U.S. government. In August, 2024, it was acquired by SIXGEN, a cybersecurity company.</p>
